    question: "Identify the logical fallacy in this example:\\n\\n«No birds are mammals. All Whales are mammals. Therefore, all Whales are birds.»",
    options: ["Invalid Syllogism", "False Dilemma", "Appeal to Ignorance", "Appeal to Tradition"],
    correct_option_index: 0,
    explanation: "The premises are “no birds are mammals” (negative) and “all whales are mammals” (affirmative), yet the conclusion is affirmative. A valid syllogism with a negative premise must have a negative conclusion.",
    detailedExplanationBeginner: "Rule: if either premise is negative, the conclusion must be negative. Here the first premise is negative, so the conclusion “all whales are birds” should be “no whales are birds” or “some whales are not birds”. The affirmative conclusion is structurally invalid.",
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: "In valid categorical syllogisms, the quality of the conclusion is determined by the premises: any negative premise forces a negative conclusion. Here the E-premise (“no birds are mammals”) requires an E or O conclusion, but the argument attempts an A conclusion.",
    detailedExplanationExpert: "This violates Rule 6: if one premise is negative, the conclusion must be negative. The correct valid conclusion from “no birds are mammals” and “all whales are mammals” is “no whales are birds” (Camestres). The given affirmative conclusion is invalid by quality.",
    questionFormat: "standard"
