    difficulty: 1,
    subLevel: SubLevel.BEGINNER,
    question: "Identify the logical fallacy in this example:\\n\\n«All Unicorns are mythical creatures. All mythical creatures are Rare Beings. Therefore, some Unicorns are Rare Beings.»",
    options: ["Invalid Syllogism", "Equivocation", "Tu Quoque", "Genetic Fallacy"],
    correct_option_index: 0,
    explanation: "The existential fallacy: universal premises (“all unicorns are mythical creatures” and “all mythical creatures are rare beings”) do not guarantee that any unicorns actually exist, so the particular conclusion “some unicorns are rare beings” does not follow.",
    detailedExplanationBeginner: "Universal statements (“all X are Y”) do not assert the existence of X. Even if all unicorns are mythical creatures and all mythical creatures are rare beings, there might be no unicorns at all. The particular conclusion “some unicorns are rare beings” requires at least one unicorns to exist, which the premises do not guarantee.",
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: "In modern Boolean logic, universal propositions are interpreted as conditionals (∀x(Ax → Bx)) and carry no existential import. Particular propositions (∃x(Ax ∧ Cx)) require existence. Deriving a particular from two universals commits the existential fallacy.",
    detailedExplanationExpert: "Aristotelian logic assumed existential import for universals, but Boolean logic rejects this. Under the Boolean interpretation, AAA-1 is valid only if the subject term is non-empty (“Barbara with existential presupposition”). Without this presupposition, moving from universals to a particular is invalid.",
    questionFormat: "standard"
