    detailedExplanationBeginner: "The statistical syllogism breaks down because authors may be a non-random subset of writers. Even if most writers are famous, the particular authors members may all lie outside famous. The inference is not truth-preserving.",
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: "This is a formal error in probabilistic reasoning. The premise “most writers are famous” can be written as P(c|b) > 0.5, but the conclusion requires P(c|a) > 0.5. Since P(c|a) is not determined by P(c|b) and a ⊆ b alone, the argument fails.",
    detailedExplanationExpert: "Base-rate neglect analogue: the conclusion ignores that authors might be concentrated in the minority region of writers. In set-theoretic terms, “most B are C” does not entail “most A are C” for arbitrary A ⊆ B without further assumptions about distribution.",
