    subLevel: SubLevel.EXPERT,
    question: "Identify the logical fallacy in this example:\\\\n\\\\n\\u00abSome fern species are non-flowering plants. Some moss species are non-flowering plants. Therefore some fern species are moss species.\\u00bb",
    options: ["Undistributed Middle", "Appeal to Authority", "Slippery Slope", "Illicit Minor"],
    correct_option_index: 0,
    explanation: "Fallacy of undistributed middle: the middle term \\\"non-flowering plants\\\" is not distributed in either premise, so no deductive connection exists between fern species and moss species.",
    detailedExplanationBeginner: "Think of \\\"non-flowering plants\\\" as a clubhouse. The argument says \\\"fern species are in the clubhouse\\\" and \\\"moss species are in the clubhouse\\\" and concludes \\\"fern species are moss species.\\\" But being in the same building does not make you the same person. The argument reveals nothing about the relationship between fern species and moss species.",
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: "Formal Logic - Intermediate. The middle term \\\"non-flowering plants\\\" must be distributed at least once in a valid categorical syllogism. Here it is not: the premises use \\\"non-flowering plants\\\" in undistributed positions (predicate of affirmative statements). Without a distributed middle term, no valid deduction follows.",
    detailedExplanationExpert: "Formal Logic - Expert. Formal analysis: the middle term \\\"non-flowering plants\\\" is not distributed in either premise. In this figure-2 syllogism, \\\"non-flowering plants\\\" occupies the predicate of affirmative statements, none of which distribute their predicates. This violates the second rule of Aristotelian syllogistic: the middle term must be distributed at least once, otherwise the dictum de omni cannot apply and the inference is formally invalid.",
    questionFormat: "standard"
